other things?

00:03:56.380 --> 00:03:57.680
And it turns out most

00:03:57.680 --> 00:04:00.680
of us don't become professional
athletes, so what are we doing?

00:04:00.680 --> 00:04:02.940
So I wanted to show
people the games do count.

00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:05.980
I talked to 73 people about
what they didn't accomplish is

00:04:05.980 --> 00:04:07.510
sports, but what they tried to,

00:04:07.510 --> 00:04:09.620
but what paid off
later down the line.

00:04:09.620 --> 00:04:11.680
Then I came out with a
how you play the game,

00:04:11.680 --> 00:04:14.940
so I wanted to weave in people
of history from Teddy Roosevelt

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:17.890
to Abraham Lincoln what they
did in sports believe it or not,

00:04:17.890 --> 00:04:21.280
that paid off to what they
became, even to Steve Young,

00:04:21.280 --> 00:04:24.270
and great athletes like Evander
Holyfield and people like you

00:04:24.270 --> 00:04:26.210
and I who didn't go pro
assuming there's not

00:04:26.210 --> 00:04:27.510
professional athletes.

00:04:27.510 --> 00:04:28.920
And to prove it doesn't matter

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:31.460
that life is what you
experience, how you handle it.

00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:33.090
You might be set
back, but you're never

00:04:33.090 --> 00:04:35.340
down unless you decide
that is it.

00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:38.500
And what do you learn from
failure or not getting success

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:41.500
to come to or come at it from
another direction, go at it,

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:43.590
go at it again and
don't give up.

00:04:43.590 --> 00:04:45.370
After that I was done.

00:04:45.370 --> 00:04:50.500
And then I started understanding
the reason when we were born

00:04:50.500 --> 00:04:52.430
in this country we
really hit the lotto.

00:04:52.430 --> 00:04:55.490
We're not a perfect country,
but man we are pretty great.

00:04:55.490 --> 00:04:57.980
And even though we don't,
we do make mistakes,

00:04:57.980 --> 00:05:03.050
for the most part, we are on
the path to getting better.

00:05:03.050 --> 00:05:05.340
And the reason why people
misinterpret what we're doing

00:05:05.340 --> 00:05:08.420
in this country is because
we have our fights in public.

00:05:08.420 --> 00:05:09.720
We let it out.

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:12.960
But we all unify behind this
principle of understanding

00:05:12.960 --> 00:05:15.020
that there's no country
like America.

00:05:15.020 --> 00:05:18.510
And after reading great history
books from Dave McCullough,

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:22.530
like John Adams, and seeing him
bring him to life, when he talks

00:05:22.530 --> 00:05:25.270
about John Adams coming into
New York and he is complaining

00:05:25.270 --> 00:05:27.070
that everybody is
rude and in a rush,

00:05:27.070 --> 00:05:29.320
I go wait a second,
they still are.

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:32.160
And I thought wow
history and today,

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:35.610
if I could bring some
humanity to this story,

00:05:35.610 --> 00:05:37.580
I can't do what Dave
McCullough does.

00:05:37.580 --> 00:05:41.370
I can't capture a famous person
like Adams or John Meacham

00:05:41.370 --> 00:05:44.580
when he grabs Push
41, or Andrew Jackson.

00:05:44.580 --> 00:05:47.390
I can't-- I don't close that
book and say I could do better,

00:05:47.390 --> 00:05:48.690
I'm not that arrogant.

00:05:48.690 --> 00:05:51.440
I don't close Grant after
reading Ron Chernow for a book

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:53.200
and say, wow that was okay.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:54.960
I think it's great.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:57.410
So what I thought I would
like to do is point out things

00:05:57.410 --> 00:05:59.660
in America's past
that shows you,

00:05:59.660 --> 00:06:01.130
you and I are what make America.

00:06:01.130 --> 00:06:03.230
As much as we love
the Founding Fathers,

00:06:03.230 --> 00:06:04.880
they live up the they hype.

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:07.000
But the people behind the
Founding Fathers made our

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:08.370
country what it is.

00:06:08.370 --> 00:06:12.790
And that's why I came up and
I looked at this for 20 years.

00:06:12.790 --> 00:06:16.920
I got it. George Washington's
Secret Six, the spy ring

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:18.860
that saved the American
Revolution.

00:06:18.860 --> 00:06:21.890
Those aren't my words,
that's what Washington said.

00:06:21.890 --> 00:06:26.300
To see a farmer, a
bartender, a printer which was

00:06:26.300 --> 00:06:29.200
like a journalist, a
grocery store owner

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:32.820
and a socialite combine forces
in three and a half years,

00:06:32.820 --> 00:06:36.830
to bring down the British and
infiltrate their headquarters

00:06:36.830 --> 00:06:40.160
and do it in a way that helps
us win the battle of Yorktown,

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:44.290
allow the French to land in
America without being confronted

00:06:44.290 --> 00:06:47.570
by the British, while outing
Benedict Arnold before he could

00:06:47.570 --> 00:06:49.960
turn over West Point,
I thought they lived

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:51.580
and died in anonymity.

00:06:51.580 --> 00:06:54.440
If I could highlight their
struggle on what they did,

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:55.990
and the credit they didn't get.

00:06:55.990 --> 00:06:59.860
Maybe I could tell a story
that America could relate to.

00:06:59.860 --> 00:07:03.370
And so called average
every day Americans turned

00:07:03.370 --> 00:07:06.450
on average every day
Americans, because the fact is

00:07:06.450 --> 00:07:09.440
without us there is
no America as much

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:11.040
as we love the man on Mount.

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:14.180
Rushmore, the people that made
America are everybody else

00:07:14.180 --> 00:07:15.480
around Mount.

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:18.120
Rushmore. So George
Washington's Secret Six opened

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:20.910
up what I thought was a venue.

00:07:20.910 --> 00:07:24.460
Take the Founding Fathers,
let the geniuses like Meacham

00:07:24.460 --> 00:07:27.450
and Brinkley and
Chernow tell that story.

00:07:27.450 --> 00:07:30.930
But what if I bring
out other elements?

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:32.450
So I came up with
Thomas Jefferson

00:07:32.450 --> 00:07:33.870
and het Tripoli Pirates.

00:07:33.870 --> 00:07:36.190
Now my problem with
Jefferson is he accomplished

00:07:36.190 --> 00:07:38.610
so much, where do you focus?

00:07:38.610 --> 00:07:41.020
Every time since 9-11
they tell the story.

00:07:41.020 --> 00:07:44.260
They say well this isn't the
first time we had a battle

00:07:44.260 --> 00:07:46.320
with radical Islamists.

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:48.440
And they refer back
to Jefferson.

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:49.740
It intrigued me.

00:07:49.740 --> 00:07:52.690
And the great people at the
Jefferson Library were able

00:07:52.690 --> 00:07:55.450
to open up their books
and show me how he took

00:07:55.450 --> 00:08:01.010
on four Muslim nations that
were stealing our ships,

00:08:01.010 --> 00:08:04.660
capturing our sailors
and capturing the cargo

00:08:04.660 --> 00:08:07.430
and demanding ransom in return.

00:08:07.430 --> 00:08:09.140
We wanted to take on this fight.

00:08:09.140 --> 00:08:14.070
The only problem was, we
had no army, we had no navy.

00:08:14.070 --> 00:08:16.480
So I came up with Thomas
Jefferson Tripoli Pirates

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:20.290
because the so called passive
presidents that did so much,

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:22.250
from Secretary of State
to the Declaration

00:08:22.250 --> 00:08:23.550
of Independence author.

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:25.690
Never really talked
much about how he took

00:08:25.690 --> 00:08:29.680
on this unpopular battle, but in
the end was praised by the pope

00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:33.590
of his time and gave America
international prestige.

00:08:33.590 --> 00:08:36.970
So here's a look right
now of Thomas Jefferson

00:08:36.970 --> 00:08:39.270
and the Tripoli Pirates.

00:08:42.530 --> 00:08:45.930
&gt;&gt; In the aftermath of
the Revolutionary war,

00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:48.560
America had won independence
from the British.

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:52.910
And that mean no more Royal Navy
to keep it sailor's safe at sea.

00:08:52.910 --> 00:08:54.620
The United States
became vulnerable

00:08:54.620 --> 00:08:58.210
to a vicious new enemy whose
extremists ideology we still

00:08:58.210 --> 00:08:59.510
face today.

00:08:59.510 --> 00:09:01.810
Islamic Radical Pirates.

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:07.260
The year, 1783, the
United States were freed,

00:09:07.260 --> 00:09:08.650
but buried in war debt.

00:09:08.650 --> 00:09:10.170
They needed to built an economy

00:09:10.170 --> 00:09:13.630
from scratch using their
greatest asset, trade.

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:16.400
The most important passageway,
the Mediterranean Sea.

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:19.530
But danger lurked right off
the North African Coast.

00:09:19.530 --> 00:09:21.170
A new enemy would await.

00:09:21.170 --> 00:09:24.950
Pirates from four
Islamic nations, Morocco,

00:09:24.950 --> 00:09:28.090
Algiers, Tunas, Tripoli.

00:09:28.090 --> 00:09:31.050
Without a navy for protection,
it's merchants were helpless

00:09:31.050 --> 00:09:32.670
and vulnerable at sea.

00:09:32.670 --> 00:09:35.760
Pirates captured our
ships, plundered our cargo

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:37.860
and turned the crew
into their slaves.

00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:41.940
Held for ransom that no new
nation could afford to pay.

00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:44.820
Without trade, America's
economy would surely collapse.

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:46.690
Congress tasked two
future Presidents

00:09:46.690 --> 00:09:47.990
to come up with a deal.

00:09:47.990 --> 00:09:50.070
John Adams and Thomas Jefferson.

00:09:50.070 --> 00:09:53.900
They'd need Tripoli's Ambassador
in London face to face.

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:56.310
The Ambassador was
charming but uncompromising.

00:09:56.310 --> 00:10:00.060
And demanded money for passage.

00:10:00.060 --> 00:10:02.680
According to the Quran it
was their God given right.

00:10:02.680 --> 00:10:05.280
Both Adams and Jefferson
left the meeting shaken.

00:10:05.280 --> 00:10:07.030
They didn't have a
deal on the prisoners,

00:10:07.030 --> 00:10:08.330
and they didn't have a deal

00:10:08.330 --> 00:10:10.370
on safe passage for
a merchant ships.

00:10:10.370 --> 00:10:12.890
Back in the United States they
waited for a recommendation.

00:10:12.890 --> 00:10:14.920
And that's where Adams
and Jefferson split.

00:10:14.920 --> 00:10:17.500
Adams said we can't
fight them unless we want

00:10:17.500 --> 00:10:18.800
to fight them forever.

00:10:18.800 --> 00:10:21.250
For Jefferson he says
you can't pay for peace.

00:10:21.250 --> 00:10:23.030
He says that the
attacks would start

00:10:23.030 --> 00:10:24.770
and the price would only go up.

00:10:24.770 --> 00:10:27.440
In this case, Jefferson
was 100 percent correct.

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:31.960
The United States would cave to
the pirates, borrowing money.

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:33.640
It would cost them
up to 20 percent

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:37.460
of their national budget, yet
somehow the attacks continued.

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:39.660
When our first President took
office, he would continue

00:10:39.660 --> 00:10:40.960
to make the payments,

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:43.280
but he would also commission
the building of six ships,

00:10:43.280 --> 00:10:46.030
including this very one,
the USS Constitution.

00:10:46.030 --> 00:10:47.330
What were they like?

00:10:47.330 --> 00:10:50.890
Well they had copper bottoms,
they had solid oak sides,

00:10:50.890 --> 00:10:52.250
they were fast, they
were strong,

00:10:52.250 --> 00:10:54.470
and they were built to fight.

00:10:54.470 --> 00:10:56.670
They wouldn't be ready for
the Washington Administration,

00:10:56.670 --> 00:10:59.720
Adams would choose not to use
them during his years in office,

00:10:59.720 --> 00:11:02.300
but for Jefferson, he knew
exactly what he was going to do.

00:11:02.300 --> 00:11:04.410
He was going to take
on the barbary nations,

00:11:04.410 --> 00:11:08.270
and the first ones to
declare war on us, Tripoli.

00:11:08.270 --> 00:11:09.800
Without congressional
approval all

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:11.980
of Thomas Jefferson's new
navy would be permitted

00:11:11.980 --> 00:11:14.620
to do would be to provide
security for the merchant ships

00:11:14.620 --> 00:11:16.690
and blockade the Tripoli harbor.

00:11:16.690 --> 00:11:19.430
The hope was to stop all
commerce coming in and out.

00:11:19.430 --> 00:11:21.010
It strangled the
Tripoli economy.

00:11:21.010 --> 00:11:22.820
Have a quick end to
this confrontation.

00:11:22.820 --> 00:11:25.570
However, the blockade was
ineffective, it was leaking.

00:11:25.570 --> 00:11:27.250
The Tripoli pirates
still had to get through,

00:11:27.250 --> 00:11:29.460
the Cruisers had the
dial and the knowledge

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:31.650
and the guts to take
on the navy.

00:11:31.650 --> 00:11:35.450
Therefore the quick end to this
clash would go by the boards.

00:11:35.450 --> 00:11:38.830
But that would change with this
captain, Edward [inaudible].

00:11:38.830 --> 00:11:41.300
The training would get hence.

00:11:41.300 --> 00:11:45.980
And the confrontation
could begin.

00:11:45.980 --> 00:11:47.870
[Inaudible] boys
were brave and brash.

00:11:47.870 --> 00:11:49.590
They confronted the pirates,

00:11:49.590 --> 00:11:51.860
harassed their ships
and took them back.

00:11:51.860 --> 00:11:54.610
Even blew up an American
ship, the USS Philadelphia

00:11:54.610 --> 00:11:57.190
that the pirates once
claimed as their prize.

00:11:57.190 --> 00:11:59.280
Soon the navy sealed the harbor.

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:01.640
Day after day their cannons
would pound the coast.

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:03.830
But Tripoli's leader
refused to budge.

00:12:03.830 --> 00:12:05.450
The navy needed a
more powerful force,

00:12:05.450 --> 00:12:08.020
both on water and on land.

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:11.660
Enter William Eaton and a
handful of fearless US marines.

00:12:11.660 --> 00:12:14.440
They launched the land war,
recruiting mercenaries,

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:17.240
enlisting the deposed
Tripoli ruler and his fighters

00:12:17.240 --> 00:12:20.160
to march 500 plus miles on foot.

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:22.840
And after the trek they
took the port city of Derna

00:12:22.840 --> 00:12:24.350
in two and a half hours.

00:12:24.350 --> 00:12:26.930
Eaton's stunning success
surprised even Jefferson,

00:12:26.930 --> 00:12:28.980
although ultimately his
victories would be stymied

00:12:28.980 --> 00:12:30.510
by a surprising source,

00:12:30.510 --> 00:12:33.250
an American diplomat
named Tobias Lear.

00:12:33.250 --> 00:12:35.460
Lear would cut a premature
peach deal with Tripoli,

00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:36.760
stopping William Eaton

00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:38.860
from taking Benghazi
and Tripoli itself.

00:12:38.860 --> 00:12:40.290
In the end it would
be another ten years

00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:43.030
and another president before
we ultimately won this war.

00:12:43.030 --> 00:12:46.380
But in the end, the message was
sent, America was a naval power,

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:49.010
would fight for liberty and
assert itself as a world leader,

00:12:49.010 --> 00:12:51.410
a position we will hold today.

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:56.580
&gt;&gt; So that was the battle
with Tunisia, Algeria, Morocco

00:12:56.580 --> 00:12:58.290
and Tripoli which is Libya,

00:12:58.290 --> 00:13:01.130
and at the same time we have
our confrontation with Libya,

00:13:01.130 --> 00:13:03.510
the overthrow of Gaddafi,
what's happened since.

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:07.630
And we begin to hear terms like
Tripoli again and Benghazi again

00:13:07.630 --> 00:13:09.180
and the confrontation again.

00:13:09.180 --> 00:13:10.950
But if you look at
Portugal, you look at Spain,

00:13:10.950 --> 00:13:12.790
you look at England, they
had one thing in common.

00:13:12.790 --> 00:13:14.680
They wanted no part
of this battle.

00:13:14.680 --> 00:13:17.200
But our country, just a
couple of decades old,

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:19.960
a couple of years old,
was in a confrontation.

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:21.620
We had to wait for a president,

00:13:21.620 --> 00:13:23.450
we had the Articles
of Confederation.

00:13:23.450 --> 00:13:26.020
And once we had that president,
he did not want to act.

00:13:26.020 --> 00:13:28.910
The next president says,
we can't fight these guys

00:13:28.910 --> 00:13:30.210
because I've seen the
look in their eye,

00:13:30.210 --> 00:13:31.510
they're going to fight forever.

00:13:31.510 --> 00:13:33.270
And they don't represent
the Muslim people.

00:13:33.270 --> 00:13:34.870
These people, the Muslim
people were oppressed

00:13:34.870 --> 00:13:36.170
by horrible leaders.

00:13:36.170 --> 00:13:37.470
They're great people.

00:13:37.470 --> 00:13:40.830
Our ambassadors love the
people of these nations,

00:13:40.830 --> 00:13:42.130
but they hated the leaders

00:13:42.130 --> 00:13:43.550
because they were
corrupt and oppressive.

00:13:43.550 --> 00:13:46.360
For William Eaton,
you know Jefferson,

00:13:46.360 --> 00:13:49.270
you might know Edward
Prebble, but for William Eaton,

00:13:49.270 --> 00:13:51.320
here's a guy whose
self-educated,

00:13:51.320 --> 00:13:54.410
put himself through
college, became this warrior

00:13:54.410 --> 00:13:58.010
and then kept pitching to,
to President Jefferson.

00:13:58.010 --> 00:14:01.730
Hey, Mr. President, I could
go get a handful of marines,

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:04.310
I'll go get some mercenaries
and I'll take these countries.

00:14:04.310 --> 00:14:05.610
I know what makes them up.

00:14:05.610 --> 00:14:06.910
We'll take them out.

00:14:06.910 --> 00:14:08.330
Jefferson said, hey
calm it, calm down,

00:14:08.330 --> 00:14:09.630
I got the ships, we'll be okay.

00:14:09.630 --> 00:14:13.030
Well just a, a sea war
was not going to do.

00:14:13.030 --> 00:14:16.050
Finally gets-- he gets him about
1,000 muskets, a little bit

00:14:16.050 --> 00:14:17.850
of money, sends him into Egypt.

00:14:17.850 --> 00:14:22.810
He gets a, a land force
together with Presley O'Bannon

00:14:22.810 --> 00:14:26.450
and they do something that all
those other nations couldn't do.

00:14:26.450 --> 00:14:28.790
They took on the
Muslim terrorists

00:14:28.790 --> 00:14:30.090
and they overthrew them.

00:14:30.090 --> 00:14:32.400
And when they took Derna,
you know what they said?

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:36.440
Guys, I'm not your leader, go
do what you want, open up shops,

00:14:36.440 --> 00:14:37.740
I'm not going to oppress you.

00:14:37.740 --> 00:14:41.360
But we pulled out early again,
leaving those people back

00:14:41.360 --> 00:14:43.230
to the old leadership.

00:14:43.230 --> 00:14:44.750
And then it took
Madison to go back,

00:14:44.750 --> 00:14:46.590
because the started
taking our guys again,

00:14:46.590 --> 00:14:48.170
to settle everything up.

00:14:48.170 --> 00:14:50.880
And in case you think this is
an American author thinking

00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:52.180
that America's great,

00:14:52.180 --> 00:14:54.200
let me tell you what Pope
Pius said at the time.

00:14:54.200 --> 00:14:56.120
And by the way it's
Pope Pius IV,

00:14:56.120 --> 00:14:58.600
I thought three Pope Pius' would
have been enough, but they need

00:14:58.600 --> 00:15:00.530
to go back to Pius again.

00:15:00.530 --> 00:15:04.420
The Americans, with a small
force and a short space of time,

00:15:04.420 --> 00:15:06.420
have done more for the
cause of Christianity

00:15:06.420 --> 00:15:07.920
than the most powerful nations

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:11.140
of Christendom have
done for ages.

00:15:11.140 --> 00:15:12.490
So we acted.

00:15:12.490 --> 00:15:14.760
The next thing you know
we're in the War of 1812.

00:15:14.760 --> 00:15:19.080
But I thought also, Jefferson,
a deed thinker, an intellectual,

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:20.480
who was asked to get
a militia together

00:15:20.480 --> 00:15:23.510
for the Revolutionary War
said, I'm more of a thinker.

00:15:23.510 --> 00:15:26.470
He knew the rest of
the world was watching.

00:15:26.470 --> 00:15:29.950
And Jefferson said this,
weakness provokes insult

00:15:29.950 --> 00:15:33.710
and injury, a condition to
punish and it often prevents.

00:15:33.710 --> 00:15:36.010
I think in our interest,
it's in our interest

00:15:36.010 --> 00:15:37.590
to punish the first insult,

00:15:37.590 --> 00:15:41.990
because insult unpunished is
the parent of many others.

00:15:41.990 --> 00:15:44.920
That is why he said
we had to fight.

00:15:44.920 --> 00:15:47.790
Adams had a great argument,
we didn't have much of a navy,

00:15:47.790 --> 00:15:49.090
they weren't experienced.

00:15:49.090 --> 00:15:50.390
And guess what America did?

00:15:50.390 --> 00:15:54.170
Started off strong, got it
wrong, rotated out our admirals,

00:15:54.170 --> 00:15:55.500
got the right guys in there,

00:15:55.500 --> 00:15:57.830
got better coordination
and sent a message.

00:15:57.830 --> 00:16:01.060
And I would argue, without that
message we don't have this much

00:16:01.060 --> 00:16:04.230
naval success in
the War of 1812.

00:16:04.230 --> 00:16:06.010
So that book seems to resonate,

00:16:06.010 --> 00:16:08.500
and our hope is we'll be
announcing a three part series

00:16:08.500 --> 00:16:10.240
on the History Channel shortly.

00:16:10.240 --> 00:16:12.860
Keep your fingers
crossed if you can,

00:16:12.860 --> 00:16:14.510
because I think it's
an important story

00:16:14.510 --> 00:16:16.220
that has to be told.

00:16:16.220 --> 00:16:20.200
So then I thought, what would
be great to talk about next?

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:22.030
I don't know if anyone here
has toured the White House?

00:16:22.030 --> 00:16:24.570
Have you guys toured it?

00:16:24.570 --> 00:16:29.070
Well I had a chance to tour it,
and they showed me the archway

00:16:29.070 --> 00:16:31.040
where they burned the
White House to the ground,

00:16:31.040 --> 00:16:32.770
and the original
flames are still there.

00:16:32.770 --> 00:16:34.070
It's right by the bowling alley.

00:16:34.070 --> 00:16:35.690
If you ever get a
chance check it out,

00:16:35.690 --> 00:16:38.700
because they wanted America
to remember how close it came

00:16:38.700 --> 00:16:40.070
to all coming to an end.

00:16:40.070 --> 00:16:42.120
Well when we had
social studies class,

00:16:42.120 --> 00:16:44.830
I could not get enough
of the War of 1812.

00:16:44.830 --> 00:16:47.300
I could not understand why we
didn't spend much more time

00:16:47.300 --> 00:16:48.600
on it.

00:16:48.600 --> 00:16:49.900
Well it was a draw, they
signed a peace treaty,

00:16:49.900 --> 00:16:51.200
they had this battle afterwards.

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:54.270
You know with-- some people
said it was an unnecessary war.

00:16:54.270 --> 00:16:55.990
Well the more I studied it,

00:16:55.990 --> 00:16:57.880
the more I realized
how close we came

00:16:57.880 --> 00:16:59.530
to utter extinction
and division.

00:16:59.530 --> 00:17:03.290
I mean for the most part,
the vote was overwhelming,

00:17:03.290 --> 00:17:06.340
but the northern states didn't
want any part of this war.

00:17:06.340 --> 00:17:07.640
They said, hey you
know what England,

00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:09.930
if you don't attack us maybe
we'll go back with you.

00:17:09.930 --> 00:17:11.810
We're tried of the
Jefferson embargo.

00:17:11.810 --> 00:17:13.930
I'm not really into
taking you guys on.

00:17:13.930 --> 00:17:15.850
And we just want to get
our economy growing.

00:17:15.850 --> 00:17:18.950
And most of the votes
came from the south.

00:17:18.950 --> 00:17:21.890
So when the war started we had a
very little army and we thought

00:17:21.890 --> 00:17:25.410
to ourselves, wait a second,
let's take on England,

00:17:25.410 --> 00:17:28.570
we think they're taking our
sailors against our will,

00:17:28.570 --> 00:17:30.190
so we're going to take them on.

00:17:30.190 --> 00:17:32.770
Let's send our army up
to Canada to fight them.

00:17:32.770 --> 00:17:34.230
It doesn't seem like
a great idea.

00:17:34.230 --> 00:17:35.530
It wasn't.

00:17:35.530 --> 00:17:38.420
We left our whole east
seaboard wide open.

00:17:38.420 --> 00:17:39.720
What do the British do?

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:41.020
Terrorize.

00:17:41.020 --> 00:17:42.320
We're losing badly.

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:44.270
Jackson put his hand
up early and said,

00:17:44.270 --> 00:17:47.810
I've got a militia I want to
fight, I want to get revenge.

00:17:47.810 --> 00:17:49.550
So please call on me.

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:52.660
The Virginia base said,
no, we got this handled.

00:17:52.660 --> 00:17:53.960
They didn't.

00:17:53.960 --> 00:17:56.170
Sooner or later they
had to call on Jackson.

00:17:56.170 --> 00:17:59.370
So this is the story that led to
the battle that I think is one

00:17:59.370 --> 00:18:01.680
of the most biggest
upsets in military history,

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:04.360
certainly in American
history, and can I just say

00:18:04.360 --> 00:18:06.870
on a partisan basis,
I'm glad we won.

00:18:06.870 --> 00:18:10.310
Here is Andrew Jackson and
the Miracle of New Orleans.

00:18:10.310 --> 00:18:16.050
&gt;&gt; The War of 1812,
America's second war

00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:19.380
of independence was going
terribly for the United States.

00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:21.960
&gt;&gt; We were so weak, we've
got just the worst generals,

00:18:21.960 --> 00:18:23.350
we've got no plan.

00:18:23.350 --> 00:18:25.200
&gt;&gt; The British, the
world's premiere economic

00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:27.880
and military power,
thirsted for a second shot

00:18:27.880 --> 00:18:29.230
at destroying America

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:32.360
after losing the Revolutionary
War 23 years earlier.

00:18:32.360 --> 00:18:35.210
The most perilous and bleak
time for the United States?

00:18:35.210 --> 00:18:37.580
The invasion and
burning of Washington,

00:18:37.580 --> 00:18:39.660
including the White House.

00:18:39.660 --> 00:18:40.960
&gt;&gt; But here is the hermitage,

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:43.290
Major General Andrew
Jackson was seething.

00:18:43.290 --> 00:18:46.000
And his country was
losing this war badly.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:47.620
America needed a leader.

00:18:47.620 --> 00:18:50.460
Without a standing army,
for President Madison,

00:18:50.460 --> 00:18:53.170
America's utter future
hung in the balance.

00:18:53.170 --> 00:18:55.320
He found his leader in Jackson.

00:18:55.320 --> 00:18:56.620
His greatest challenge?

00:18:56.620 --> 00:18:59.340
Stopping the British forces
from taking New Orleans.

00:18:59.340 --> 00:19:01.100
&gt;&gt; He lost New Orleans

00:19:01.100 --> 00:19:03.070
and if the British
controlled the great city,

00:19:03.070 --> 00:19:06.660
you lose the entire Mississippi
River and you lose all

00:19:06.660 --> 00:19:10.020
of our western frontier that we
acquired through the purchase.

00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:13.350
So we wouldn't have been
able to do western expansion.

00:19:13.350 --> 00:19:18.060
&gt;&gt; The plan, build a wall, dig
a canal, fill it with water,

00:19:18.060 --> 00:19:20.820
and wait for a British charge.

00:19:20.820 --> 00:19:24.210
This berm, this protection,
this wall was built in a matter

00:19:24.210 --> 00:19:27.210
of weeks, miles long to
protect Andrew Jackson

00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:28.510
and the American troops.

00:19:28.510 --> 00:19:31.420
Over there, with
thousands of British troops,

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:33.430
what they wanted
that was New Orleans.

00:19:33.430 --> 00:19:34.730
What's at stake?

00:19:34.730 --> 00:19:36.030
The future of the country.

00:19:36.030 --> 00:19:39.680
&gt;&gt; His mishmash of troops that
comes in part Choctaw Indians,

00:19:39.680 --> 00:19:43.630
Kentucky and Tennessee militia,
[inaudible], rifles and free men

00:19:43.630 --> 00:19:47.260
of color, they're not going to
go out and engage the British.

00:19:47.260 --> 00:19:49.580
Jackson knows that
would be suicide.

00:19:49.580 --> 00:19:52.410
&gt;&gt; Any expert would tell you
Jackson's ragtag army would need

00:19:52.410 --> 00:19:55.010
a miracle to stop the British
from spending Christmas

00:19:55.010 --> 00:19:57.610
on Bourbon Street,
and Jackson knew just

00:19:57.610 --> 00:20:00.060
where to go to ask for it.

00:20:00.060 --> 00:20:01.970
&gt;&gt; Why would I be outside
a convent when I'm trying

00:20:01.970 --> 00:20:03.610
to tell the Battle
of New Orleans?

00:20:03.610 --> 00:20:05.970
Because this isn't just any
convent, this is the home

00:20:05.970 --> 00:20:08.820
of the Ursuline Nuns, it
dates back hundreds of years.

00:20:08.820 --> 00:20:10.500
They prayed for Jackson's
success.

00:20:10.500 --> 00:20:12.580
And among the people who think

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:15.180
that these nuns brought
his a miraculous victory?

00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:17.830
Major General Andrew
Jackson himself.

00:20:17.830 --> 00:20:20.560
&gt;&gt; It's the miracle, it's
praying for a miracle,

00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:22.860
the Catholic Church and
the Battle of New Orleans.

00:20:22.860 --> 00:20:26.030
I mean that is where we know

00:20:26.030 --> 00:20:27.640
that there was divine
intervention.

00:20:27.640 --> 00:20:30.900
&gt;&gt; And that divine
intervention would reveal itself

00:20:30.900 --> 00:20:34.240
in the final fight
January 8, 1815.

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:36.540
&gt;&gt; This becomes a
blood bath here.

00:20:36.540 --> 00:20:39.330
The purposes, now we're
just in a green grass.

00:20:39.330 --> 00:20:41.820
It was the beginning
of the end of Britain

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:44.380
and in many ways the
birth of modern America.

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:46.810
&gt;&gt; Jackson's forceful
leadership would help record one

00:20:46.810 --> 00:20:48.130
of the most decisive

00:20:48.130 --> 00:20:52.690
and stunning upset
victories in military history.

00:20:52.690 --> 00:20:55.340
But Andrew Jackson left
his estate, before the War

00:20:55.340 --> 00:20:57.370
of 1812, he was known locally.

00:20:57.370 --> 00:20:58.670
When he was done
winning the Battle

00:20:58.670 --> 00:21:01.000
of New Orleans he
became a national star.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.430
Maybe the most famous
person in America.

00:21:03.430 --> 00:21:06.200
But more importantly his wins
sent a message to the rest

00:21:06.200 --> 00:21:08.550
of the world, that we
would fight relentlessly

00:21:08.550 --> 00:21:10.650
and furiously for freedom.

00:21:10.650 --> 00:21:13.020
As for Jackson, he would
ride that fame for two terms

00:21:13.020 --> 00:21:16.000
in the White House and go down
as one of the most consequential

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.270
and influential Americans
in our history.

00:21:20.610 --> 00:21:23.590
&gt;&gt; And that's this the hard
back that came out last year,

00:21:23.590 --> 00:21:25.890
Andrew Jackson, the
Miracle of New Orleans.

00:21:25.890 --> 00:21:30.850
So if you think about it, the
army that just beat Napoleon,

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:33.850
Wellington's invincibles, they
get together and they say,

00:21:33.850 --> 00:21:35.250
let's just wipe out America.

00:21:35.250 --> 00:21:39.440
Let's stop America from growing
past the Mississippi River.

00:21:39.440 --> 00:21:42.810
We are going to stay and we're
going to stop this growth.

00:21:42.810 --> 00:21:44.920
They saw us as a rival,
they saw the potential

00:21:44.920 --> 00:21:48.100
that we could have, and
they thought they had it.

00:21:48.100 --> 00:21:51.470
Now in case you thought that
I'm overestimating that,

00:21:51.470 --> 00:21:53.730
here's what the British
Foreign Secretary said,

00:21:53.730 --> 00:21:56.400
while they're trying to
negotiate the Treaty of Ghent.

00:21:56.400 --> 00:21:59.360
I expect, at this moment, that
most of the large seaport towns

00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:02.260
of America are laid to ashes,
that we're in possession

00:22:02.260 --> 00:22:05.040
of New Orleans and have command
of the Mississippi Valley,

00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:06.640
that Mississippi
River and lakes.

00:22:06.640 --> 00:22:08.750
And that the Americans
are now little better

00:22:08.750 --> 00:22:11.260
than prisoners in
their own country.

00:22:11.260 --> 00:22:14.610
So what stopped that
from happening?

00:22:14.610 --> 00:22:15.910
Andrew Jackson.

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:18.240
This instinctive
military leadership.

00:22:18.240 --> 00:22:20.330
He didn't come from
the academies.

00:22:20.330 --> 00:22:24.580
The guy was brought up outside
the so-called Virginia base,

00:22:24.580 --> 00:22:27.550
or the Boston power base.

00:22:27.550 --> 00:22:28.850
Either one of these.

00:22:28.850 --> 00:22:31.860
He was the first outside to
actually rise to prominence.

00:22:31.860 --> 00:22:33.330
And what did he go through?

00:22:33.330 --> 00:22:36.030
And I didn't realize this
until I started researching it.

00:22:36.030 --> 00:22:38.130
What he went thorough
was the ultimate

00:22:38.130 --> 00:22:40.880
and maybe the first
rags to riches story.

00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:42.870
I mean his parents come
here from Scotland.

00:22:42.870 --> 00:22:45.700
His dad dies before he was born.

00:22:45.700 --> 00:22:47.590
His mom raises three kids

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:50.340
by just basically being a
housekeeper for other people,

00:22:50.340 --> 00:22:53.270
doing whatever she can to
get through, very tough times

00:22:53.270 --> 00:22:56.040
in the Tennessee /
South Carolina area.

00:22:56.040 --> 00:22:58.440
And then when a time for
the war, of the older son,

00:22:58.440 --> 00:23:00.750
they knew one thing they
didn't like the British

00:23:00.750 --> 00:23:02.400
because they're Scottish.

00:23:02.400 --> 00:23:03.700
He goes to fight.

00:23:03.700 --> 00:23:05.420
He dies of heat stroke.

00:23:05.420 --> 00:23:09.120
So the two, 13 and 14 years
old, Robert and Andrew,

00:23:09.120 --> 00:23:12.020
start becoming couriers
in the Revolutionary War.

00:23:12.020 --> 00:23:15.050
Well they get caught,
followed back to a house,

00:23:15.050 --> 00:23:17.430
and the British soldier
says clean my boots

00:23:17.430 --> 00:23:19.650
to both brothers,
and they both say no.

00:23:19.650 --> 00:23:22.940
Up come up the sword,
down goes the sword,

00:23:22.940 --> 00:23:25.520
right to the brother's
head, a direct hit.

00:23:25.520 --> 00:23:28.550
Andrew puts his hand up,
he'd have the scar the rest

00:23:28.550 --> 00:23:31.090
of his life, but he was
able to parry the blow.

00:23:31.090 --> 00:23:33.760
They went to prison,
after walking 20 miles,

00:23:33.760 --> 00:23:35.930
after they take their
shoes off, in the winter.

00:23:35.930 --> 00:23:37.320
They spent a couple
of years there.

00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:38.700
But you know what stopped them?

00:23:38.700 --> 00:23:40.620
The mom was relentless
to get them out.

00:23:40.620 --> 00:23:42.980
But by the time they
got back to their house,

00:23:42.980 --> 00:23:45.910
they were so sick
that Robert died.

00:23:45.910 --> 00:23:49.000
And it's just Andrew
and his mom.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:50.910
So they need money.

00:23:50.910 --> 00:23:53.490
So she goes to a
cousin to earn money.

00:23:53.490 --> 00:23:57.220
A trunk ends up on the doorstep
of Andrew Jackson's house.

00:23:57.220 --> 00:23:58.620
It's his mom's stuff.

00:23:58.620 --> 00:24:02.040
He still lived and died
without knowing how she died.

00:24:02.040 --> 00:24:04.910
He is alone at 14 years old.

00:24:04.910 --> 00:24:06.940
A war veteran you could say.

00:24:06.940 --> 00:24:11.120
He was raised by his town,
he was raised by his village,

00:24:11.120 --> 00:24:13.030
he was raised by his country.

00:24:13.030 --> 00:24:15.610
Therefore he bled
red, white and blue.

00:24:15.610 --> 00:24:19.820
He became a self-taught
lawyer, a judge, a congressman,

00:24:19.820 --> 00:24:23.090
a senator, a major general
and then when the War

00:24:23.090 --> 00:24:25.940
of 1812 happened,
what is he thinking?

00:24:25.940 --> 00:24:28.970
Revenge. Put me in coach.

00:24:28.970 --> 00:24:30.270
They didn't.

00:24:30.270 --> 00:24:32.710
You're a backwoodsman, you don't
really know what you're doing.

00:24:32.710 --> 00:24:34.900
You didn't go to West Pointe.

00:24:34.900 --> 00:24:36.880
But he could lead,
he couldn't get

00:24:36.880 --> 00:24:40.960
through when all the other
guys failed, he got through.

00:24:40.960 --> 00:24:43.740
And all he did was roll,
roll off battle win,

00:24:43.740 --> 00:24:46.050
after battle win, but
he knew they were going

00:24:46.050 --> 00:24:47.350
to go for New Orleans.

00:24:47.350 --> 00:24:49.080
But he didn't have enough guys.

00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:51.770
So he had to get free
men of color, Cassian's,

00:24:51.770 --> 00:24:53.970
make a deal with local pirates,

00:24:53.970 --> 00:24:57.090
had Tennessee riflemen,
Kentucky riflemen.

00:24:57.090 --> 00:24:58.660
He put them together
in three weeks.

00:24:58.660 --> 00:25:01.040
He got the whole
town to dig a ditch.

00:25:01.040 --> 00:25:03.590
And if just in case he walked
into New Orleans and felt

00:25:03.590 --> 00:25:06.280
as though they weren't
all in, he let them know.

00:25:06.280 --> 00:25:09.350
If you don't fight with me I'm
burning this town to the ground.

00:25:09.350 --> 00:25:12.070
It turns out they were
all in after that.

00:25:12.070 --> 00:25:15.570
Then he said, the British
are going to land here.

00:25:15.570 --> 00:25:17.260
What do I do?

00:25:17.260 --> 00:25:18.740
Stop here.

00:25:18.740 --> 00:25:21.530
What happens if we don't, if
they get through our first line?

00:25:21.530 --> 00:25:23.380
Dig another line.

00:25:23.380 --> 00:25:26.900
Told them there's no
substitute for winning.

00:25:26.900 --> 00:25:29.200
They knew by the time
this battle started they

00:25:29.200 --> 00:25:30.500
couldn't miss.

00:25:30.500 --> 00:25:31.800
You know what they had better?

00:25:31.800 --> 00:25:34.090
They had better riflemen,
they were more determined,

00:25:34.090 --> 00:25:35.860
because the British
were not fighting

00:25:35.860 --> 00:25:38.930
for their freedom they were
fighting to stop growth

00:25:38.930 --> 00:25:41.410
of a free nation, many
of which wanted to stay

00:25:41.410 --> 00:25:43.190
and ended up staying here.

00:25:43.190 --> 00:25:45.740
So listen to these numbers.

00:25:45.740 --> 00:25:53.870
In under 45 minutes, we
have 13 dead they have 291.

00:25:53.870 --> 00:25:58.210
We have 5,300 fighters
they have 10,000.

00:25:58.210 --> 00:26:05.750
We have 39 wounded, they
have 1,262, 484 are missing

00:26:05.750 --> 00:26:07.620
which means essentially
they were blown apart.

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:11.200
We took out three generals,
seven colonels, 75 officers.

00:26:11.200 --> 00:26:13.450
So why is it that
Andrew Jackson was able

00:26:13.450 --> 00:26:15.550
to do what Napoleon couldn't?

00:26:15.550 --> 00:26:18.960
Because I believe on some
level America was meant

00:26:18.960 --> 00:26:21.910
for something special, to the,
to be the beacon of freedom

00:26:21.910 --> 00:26:24.000
of the world it doesn't
mean we're perfect,

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:25.440
but it means we're like no other

00:26:25.440 --> 00:26:28.280
and it means we have a
responsibility to do so.

00:26:28.280 --> 00:26:31.560
And for those who say the battle
did not have to be taught,

00:26:31.560 --> 00:26:33.740
because that's what they
taught us in school,

00:26:33.740 --> 00:26:36.330
this is what Jackson said.

00:26:36.330 --> 00:26:39.090
If General Pakenham, which by
the way was the brother-in-law

00:26:39.090 --> 00:26:40.390
of Wellington.

00:26:40.390 --> 00:26:42.720
Wellington's like yeah, I fought
already, I'm not into going

00:26:42.720 --> 00:26:44.670
to America, but you're
my brother-in-law,

00:26:44.670 --> 00:26:47.110
so why don't you take my
army and go, and you can stay

00:26:47.110 --> 00:26:49.090
and be the governor,
it'll be easy.

00:26:49.090 --> 00:26:50.390
It wasn't.

00:26:50.390 --> 00:26:53.150
General Pakenham and his
10,000 matched with veterans,

00:26:53.150 --> 00:26:55.530
if they could have alienated
my little army he would have

00:26:55.530 --> 00:26:56.830
captured New Orleans

00:26:56.830 --> 00:26:59.470
and sentried all the
contiguous territory,

00:26:59.470 --> 00:27:01.320
so technically the war was over,

00:27:01.320 --> 00:27:03.360
Great Britain would have
immediately aggregated the

00:27:03.360 --> 00:27:06.090
treaty again, would have
ignored Jefferson's transaction

00:27:06.090 --> 00:27:07.390
with Napoleon.

00:27:07.390 --> 00:27:10.560
That means no Louisiana
Purchase.

00:27:10.560 --> 00:27:11.860
It means the country of--

00:27:11.860 --> 00:27:14.070
our country wouldn't
have doubled in size.

00:27:14.070 --> 00:27:15.890
It means our Washington
was burned,

00:27:15.890 --> 00:27:18.730
our five foot three inch
president was on his own.

00:27:18.730 --> 00:27:21.570
Our records were scattered
out throughout the country.

00:27:21.570 --> 00:27:24.190
We were over, we were
finished we were through.

00:27:24.190 --> 00:27:27.570
If not for this 14 year old
who finally found a way to get

00:27:27.570 --> 00:27:30.060
out of prison thanks
to a relentless mom,

00:27:30.060 --> 00:27:32.360
who was determined to
pay back his country,

00:27:32.360 --> 00:27:33.900
and pay back the British.

00:27:33.900 --> 00:27:36.370
I did not know when
I dove into this

00:27:36.370 --> 00:27:37.960
that I'd come out with this.

00:27:37.960 --> 00:27:40.430
I did not know I'd be talking
about what I thought was one

00:27:40.430 --> 00:27:41.850
of the original American
success story

00:27:41.850 --> 00:27:43.310
and the promise of
our country as.

00:27:43.310 --> 00:27:47.370
That if you do whatever you
can, if you believe in yourself,

00:27:47.370 --> 00:27:49.280
and you are determined
to be successful,

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:52.550
you'll have the opportunity
to pursue happiness/success.

00:27:52.550 --> 00:27:54.260
That's what he was
trying to say.

00:27:54.260 --> 00:27:56.340
And when he rose up
through the ranks,

00:27:56.340 --> 00:27:59.520
he wasn't representing the
rich, the famous, the powerful,

00:27:59.520 --> 00:28:02.640
he was representing the
so-called average every day

00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:04.400
Americans doing extraordinary
things

00:28:04.400 --> 00:28:06.070
to keep our country alive.

00:28:06.070 --> 00:28:07.370
Was he perfect?

00:28:07.370 --> 00:28:08.670
No. I'm not debating
his presidency,

00:28:08.670 --> 00:28:12.270
that's for John Mecham, he's
really smart with better hair.

00:28:12.270 --> 00:28:16.500
I wanted to grab the
moment in which he emerged

00:28:16.500 --> 00:28:21.230
at 40 something years old, as
the most famous man in America.

00:28:21.230 --> 00:28:23.360
Now when Donald Trump
puts his picture

00:28:23.360 --> 00:28:26.000
in the Oval Office
he becomes a story.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.760
In the paperback that
comes out in two months,

00:28:28.760 --> 00:28:33.170
I decided as my excerpt to
not debate Andrew Jackson,

00:28:33.170 --> 00:28:36.320
what kind of President
he was, and what he did.

00:28:36.320 --> 00:28:38.150
Because back then
when people now are,

00:28:38.150 --> 00:28:40.860
are revisiting our history
and think we know more,

00:28:40.860 --> 00:28:43.580
and I think we're coming off
as a very arrogant generation

00:28:43.580 --> 00:28:45.660
that looks back and
says how could they,

00:28:45.660 --> 00:28:47.850
no one defends slavery,
no one ever will.

00:28:47.850 --> 00:28:50.660
No one defends fighting
the Civil War

00:28:50.660 --> 00:28:54.230
and saying wow the south
was right, no one ever will.

00:28:54.230 --> 00:28:57.370
But understand these
people were, were monuments

00:28:57.370 --> 00:29:01.030
in their time, put up by people
in their day for a reason,

00:29:01.030 --> 00:29:04.140
and when you look at
Jackson we're revisiting him.

00:29:04.140 --> 00:29:06.560
So I thought I'd
revisit him with this.

00:29:06.560 --> 00:29:12.540
Lincoln, FDR, Teddy Roosevelt,
Harry Truman, Ronald Reagan,

00:29:12.540 --> 00:29:16.970
when asked who they looked
to most in times of trouble,

00:29:16.970 --> 00:29:22.220
and for setting out an agenda,
those men looked at that man.

00:29:22.220 --> 00:29:24.520
Did they look at him
because he was perfect?

00:29:24.520 --> 00:29:28.970
No. Did they look at him because
he was a self-made American

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:32.510
success story that defined
leadership in its own way?

00:29:32.510 --> 00:29:35.220
Knew how to consolidate
power, and get things done

00:29:35.220 --> 00:29:37.790
and he cared more about the
everyday people than he did

00:29:37.790 --> 00:29:41.010
about political power
and prestige.

00:29:41.010 --> 00:29:44.910
And once he left office, he
had a lot of power afterwards.

00:29:44.910 --> 00:29:47.850
So when Harry Truman took
office, he had a figurine

00:29:47.850 --> 00:29:49.320
of Jackson on his desk.

00:29:49.320 --> 00:29:54.040
Before World War II, FDR in all
his pain, locked in his braces

00:29:54.040 --> 00:29:55.790
and walked up the steps to go

00:29:55.790 --> 00:30:00.360
to the hermitage before he
put our nation again at war.

00:30:00.360 --> 00:30:03.170
When Ronald Reagan chose to give
a speech after being elected,

00:30:03.170 --> 00:30:05.460
he did it in front of
the Jackson statute.

00:30:05.460 --> 00:30:08.130
When Lincoln wanted to know how
to keep our country together,

00:30:08.130 --> 00:30:11.090
he looked back at Jackson's
papers, because Jackson said

00:30:11.090 --> 00:30:13.300
to South Caroline,
oh you want to leave,

00:30:13.300 --> 00:30:14.600
you got about one week.

00:30:14.600 --> 00:30:16.780
Because if you decide to
leave, I'm sending troops

00:30:16.780 --> 00:30:18.150
in to make sure you stay.

00:30:18.150 --> 00:30:19.880
He was going to keep
the union together.

00:30:19.880 --> 00:30:22.590
It's exactly like
Lincoln did, no?

00:30:22.590 --> 00:30:25.070
But there was something
to learn there.

00:30:25.070 --> 00:30:26.920
So I through Teddy
Roosevelt too,

00:30:26.920 --> 00:30:31.260
when he had to do a biography,
he chose Andrew Jackson.

00:30:31.260 --> 00:30:36.810
So I choose to take on passage
of where Andrew Jackson emerged

00:30:36.810 --> 00:30:39.820
and a victory that people
still can't makes sense of,

00:30:39.820 --> 00:30:42.320
they still teach
about in war colleges.

00:30:42.320 --> 00:30:44.430
My next project, which I
hope you're enthusiastic

00:30:44.430 --> 00:30:47.040
about which I can't get enough
of, and no one wants to hang

00:30:47.040 --> 00:30:48.800
out with me because I can't
stop talking about it.

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:50.950
Do you ever get that when
you're in the middle of a book,

00:30:50.950 --> 00:30:52.400
or in the middle of research?

00:30:52.400 --> 00:30:54.420
All you do is think
and talk about that?

00:30:54.420 --> 00:30:56.720
Because I'm very, very
simple, I pretty much think

00:30:56.720 --> 00:30:58.020
on one track all the time.

00:30:58.020 --> 00:31:00.910
But I'm doing Sam Houston
avenging the Alamo.

00:31:00.910 --> 00:31:04.710
And the link to Sam
Houston and Jackson

00:31:04.710 --> 00:31:08.420
to see Sam Houston fighting
in the Creek War for Jackson,

00:31:08.420 --> 00:31:11.420
getting wounded, Jackson walking
over to the sick bay and saying,

00:31:11.420 --> 00:31:13.110
I need more guys
to finish them off.

00:31:13.110 --> 00:31:16.510
And he gets up and fights
again, gets shot again.

00:31:16.510 --> 00:31:18.360
They send him back to
Washington to heal,

00:31:18.360 --> 00:31:19.660
it's burned to the ground.

00:31:19.660 --> 00:31:20.980
They think he's going to die.

00:31:20.980 --> 00:31:23.200
He lives. Jackson
would mentor him.

00:31:23.200 --> 00:31:25.260
So I thought it would
be a perfect next step

00:31:25.260 --> 00:31:28.490
and to see what Texas
has done is fascinating.

00:31:28.490 --> 00:31:31.850
I always thought you had to
be from Texas to study Texas

00:31:31.850 --> 00:31:33.820
because they get
kind of resentful.

00:31:33.820 --> 00:31:35.530
For a New Yorker to do it.

00:31:35.530 --> 00:31:38.500
But I'm finding nothing but open
arms, and I cannot wait to tell

00:31:38.500 --> 00:31:39.870
that story, and I
hope you like it.

00:31:39.870 --> 00:31:41.850
What I try to do in my books,

00:31:41.850 --> 00:31:44.280
I don't try to impress
you with a vocabulary.

00:31:44.280 --> 00:31:46.600
I don't try to get you
caught up in the background

00:31:46.600 --> 00:31:48.680
and the smell in the air.

00:31:48.680 --> 00:31:51.030
And some people don't like that.

00:31:51.030 --> 00:31:54.900
What I try to do is tell a story
that's accurate but concise

00:31:54.900 --> 00:31:56.760
that makes you want
to study more.

00:31:56.760 --> 00:31:59.120
I don't think I can do
the definitive biography,

00:31:59.120 --> 00:32:02.600
even on myself, but I
think I can grab a slice

00:32:02.600 --> 00:32:06.180
of what made these men and women
great, and tell you the story.

00:32:06.180 --> 00:32:09.940
Because really the supporting
cast matters so much.

00:32:09.940 --> 00:32:11.610
We are the supporting casts.

00:32:11.610 --> 00:32:12.910
We're not on Mount.

00:32:12.910 --> 00:32:14.210
Rushmore, but we matter.

00:32:14.210 --> 00:32:16.790
And that's what I try
to do with the books,

00:32:16.790 --> 00:32:18.330
and people have been
kind enough to get them.

00:32:18.330 --> 00:32:20.170
And I just love telling
the story.

00:32:20.170 --> 00:32:22.330
And I never thought history
would be so under attack

00:32:22.330 --> 00:32:24.590
as it is today, so I never
thought there would be

00:32:24.590 --> 00:32:27.010
so much news about
things in the past.

00:32:27.010 --> 00:32:28.310
But it's here.

00:32:28.310 --> 00:32:30.430
And I'm still going to
say America's not perfect,

00:32:30.430 --> 00:32:33.810
but man we're special and
I will always believe that.

00:32:33.810 --> 00:32:36.430
And I believe all of us, even
if we were the biggest critic

00:32:36.430 --> 00:32:39.530
of this country, we hit
lotto when we were born here.

00:32:39.530 --> 00:32:41.650
Everyday we're allowed
to thrive here.

00:32:41.650 --> 00:32:43.280
We're all in the Super Bowl.

00:32:43.280 --> 00:32:45.960
So with that I like you to
come up to the microphone

00:32:45.960 --> 00:32:47.530
and tell me how I'm wrong.

00:32:47.530 --> 00:32:49.200
Or tell me what you like.

00:32:49.200 --> 00:32:53.120
Or ask any questions about
the book and/or the radio show

00:32:53.120 --> 00:32:56.150
or Fox in the morning,
whatever you want.

00:32:56.150 --> 00:32:58.370
So unless you are
a really shy group,

00:32:58.370 --> 00:33:01.480
which I understand you're
not, because I can't even get

00:33:01.480 --> 00:33:03.430
on the elevator,
because everyone's

00:33:03.430 --> 00:33:05.170
so loud and deliberate.

00:33:05.170 --> 00:33:06.710
But I appreciate it.

00:33:06.710 --> 00:33:08.010
Yes.

00:33:08.010 --> 00:33:09.310
&gt;&gt; I'm not shy.

00:33:09.310 --> 00:33:13.030
I think you gave a great speech
and I think it's very important

00:33:13.030 --> 00:33:18.820
that we recognize the
humanity of people in history,

00:33:18.820 --> 00:33:20.760
both the good and the bad.

00:33:20.760 --> 00:33:25.900
But I really need to push back
on your view on the monuments

00:33:25.900 --> 00:33:27.830
that were erected to them.

00:33:27.830 --> 00:33:32.610
Most of those Civil War
monuments were erected after,

00:33:32.610 --> 00:33:38.860
way after the Civil War,
as a way of putting blacks

00:33:38.860 --> 00:33:42.850
in their place, and
reminding them.

00:33:48.100 --> 00:33:53.060
And reminding them of their
history in a negative way.

00:33:53.060 --> 00:33:57.540
I'm not for getting rid
of the monuments but I am

00:33:57.540 --> 00:34:00.720
for putting history in context--

00:34:00.720 --> 00:34:02.270
&gt;&gt; Well lets' talk about this.

00:34:02.270 --> 00:34:03.570
Great point.

00:34:03.570 --> 00:34:06.530
And if you read Grant
it really comes home.

00:34:06.530 --> 00:34:07.830
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:34:07.830 --> 00:34:10.540
&gt;&gt; Because reconstruction is so
underappreciated, underreported.

00:34:10.540 --> 00:34:13.040
As a white guy whose family
wasn't even in America

00:34:13.040 --> 00:34:14.340
at the time, I'm horrified

00:34:14.340 --> 00:34:16.340
that a country this great
could rationalize slavery,

00:34:16.340 --> 00:34:17.640
to be honest.

00:34:17.640 --> 00:34:18.940
I don't know what
to say about it.

00:34:18.940 --> 00:34:20.430
And I think a lot
of white people

00:34:20.430 --> 00:34:22.890
in America feel the
exact same way.

00:34:22.890 --> 00:34:26.350
But I love, like I
interviewed Jim Brown '80--

00:34:26.350 --> 00:34:29.370
I did a show with
him for five years.

00:34:29.370 --> 00:34:31.880
I interviewed him Tuesday.

00:34:31.880 --> 00:34:34.700
And he said yeah he
came from slavery

00:34:34.700 --> 00:34:36.720
but look how far we've come.

00:34:36.720 --> 00:34:38.420
And he says, when it comes

00:34:38.420 --> 00:34:43.880
to back then no one will
ever justify slavery,

00:34:43.880 --> 00:34:49.840
but in 2018 he says if a white
person in Manhasset didn't pay

00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:51.460
for my school without
telling me,

00:34:51.460 --> 00:34:53.920
I wouldn't have become the
running back from Syracuse.

00:34:53.920 --> 00:34:56.880
He says, a lot of white people
have died because slavery was

00:34:56.880 --> 00:34:58.850
so wrong and they
wanted to fix it.

00:34:58.850 --> 00:35:00.150
So I'm not going to put that.

00:35:00.150 --> 00:35:02.690
