own people.

00:44:49.920 --> 00:44:51.460
And what our ambassadors
came back and said,

00:44:51.460 --> 00:44:54.430
I love these people William
Eaton especially loved the

00:44:54.430 --> 00:44:55.730
Muslim people.

00:44:55.730 --> 00:45:00.240
He had Muslims as mercenaries
come back and take Derna

00:45:00.240 --> 00:45:02.080
in two, two and a half hours.

00:45:02.080 --> 00:45:03.550
Without them they don't win.

00:45:03.550 --> 00:45:04.920
Yes sir.

00:45:04.920 --> 00:45:06.740
&gt;&gt; You've written several
books with Don Yeager,

00:45:06.740 --> 00:45:09.370
how does the collaborative
process work between you two?

00:45:09.370 --> 00:45:13.020
&gt;&gt; Don deserves credit in
that, Don and I met in sports.

00:45:13.020 --> 00:45:15.060
And he said, let's do
another sports book.

00:45:15.060 --> 00:45:16.360
And I go Don I can't,

00:45:16.360 --> 00:45:18.240
for 20 years I've been
studying this spy ring,

00:45:18.240 --> 00:45:21.780
and I showed all these
pages, these yellow pages.

00:45:21.780 --> 00:45:23.850
So he goes back, he
goes can I take them?

00:45:23.850 --> 00:45:26.210
I go there is no other copy.

00:45:26.210 --> 00:45:27.950
So he takes them, he comes back,

00:45:27.950 --> 00:45:30.180
it was Thanksgiving
three and a half weeks.

00:45:30.180 --> 00:45:32.820
And he said, I cannot, I
think we could do more.

00:45:32.820 --> 00:45:34.810
I go Don, we can't do
this unless we approach it

00:45:34.810 --> 00:45:36.180
like a news story.

00:45:36.180 --> 00:45:41.330
So we went out to
Fort Washington,

00:45:41.330 --> 00:45:43.910
we went out to Stoneybrook,
we went out to Penny Packard,

00:45:43.910 --> 00:45:45.550
we did the original
biography in 1930

00:45:45.550 --> 00:45:47.190
and put the spy ring together.

00:45:47.190 --> 00:45:49.890
We were able to capture that
and I was able to take a lot

00:45:49.890 --> 00:45:52.180
of this oral history and put
all the experts in the same room

00:45:52.180 --> 00:45:55.610
in a Holiday Inn in Suffice
County, and I catered it.

00:45:55.610 --> 00:45:57.760
I didn't get Subway, I
went to a regular deli.

00:45:57.760 --> 00:45:59.920
And I had all these historians.

00:45:59.920 --> 00:46:03.140
And I said, first
off, whose 355?

00:46:03.140 --> 00:46:04.580
Everyone had a different theory.

00:46:04.580 --> 00:46:08.010
Second off, Robert Townsend,
did he ever meet Washington?

00:46:08.010 --> 00:46:09.310
Where did it happen?

00:46:09.310 --> 00:46:11.030
It could have been diagonally
across from Sagamore Hill.

00:46:11.030 --> 00:46:12.330
But how do we know it?

00:46:12.330 --> 00:46:13.630
Can you point to anything?

00:46:13.630 --> 00:46:15.990
And they were able to go
through all our things.

00:46:15.990 --> 00:46:18.340
So he's the one who
pushed me to do it.

00:46:18.340 --> 00:46:22.130
But he's the one who's an
organizer, an economizer

00:46:22.130 --> 00:46:24.840
of words, I'll pump
stuff out, he'll gut it,

00:46:24.840 --> 00:46:26.450
he'll give it to
me, I'll gut it.

00:46:26.450 --> 00:46:29.760
And I don't know how people do
it, but he did it in Tallahassee

00:46:29.760 --> 00:46:31.060
and I stayed in New York,

00:46:31.060 --> 00:46:33.450
and we only saw each
other three times a year.

00:46:33.450 --> 00:46:36.880
But the magic of back and forth,
back and forth, back and forth,

00:46:36.880 --> 00:46:38.880
while he's doing
Namen's biography,

00:46:38.880 --> 00:46:42.790
while he's doing Walter Peyton,
and all these other things.

00:46:42.790 --> 00:46:46.020
So he wanted to add sports
a little bit, I'm a sports

00:46:46.020 --> 00:46:48.290
because at Fox I can't
do sports anymore,

00:46:48.290 --> 00:46:50.130
that's why they have Fox Sports.

00:46:50.130 --> 00:46:52.250
So it was kind of a thing.

00:46:52.250 --> 00:46:54.770
I never thought I could
do if Don didn't push me.

00:46:54.770 --> 00:46:58.760
And after then, then I really
thought to myself, I could do it

00:46:58.760 --> 00:47:02.960
because if I just capture one
element and try to dominate it

00:47:02.960 --> 00:47:05.610
for two years, and move forward.

00:47:05.610 --> 00:47:08.120
And I made sure that John
Meacham and Douglas Brinkley

00:47:08.120 --> 00:47:10.170
and Jay Winick, I go
guys look at it, read it.

00:47:10.170 --> 00:47:12.700
If you're not comfortable
with it, let me know.

00:47:12.700 --> 00:47:15.030
And they said to me, it
works, it checks out.

00:47:15.030 --> 00:47:16.690
And they go, I'll go on
the back of the book.

00:47:16.690 --> 00:47:19.200
So that's why I felt, I
felt good about doing it.

00:47:19.200 --> 00:47:21.250
But I'm still in awe
of everybody speaking

00:47:21.250 --> 00:47:23.130
in the other room and
everything like that.

00:47:23.130 --> 00:47:24.850
What I just try to
do is tell a story

00:47:24.850 --> 00:47:27.930
that hopefully will give other
people an understanding of,

00:47:27.930 --> 00:47:29.980
of America.

00:47:29.980 --> 00:47:32.280
Thank you.

00:47:36.160 --> 00:47:37.460
Thank you very much.

